Just before Christmas, we finally ventured to a cozy little town just a stones throw from Heathrow Airport, a quick train from London - the sleepy  village of Amersham 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁥󠁮󠁧󠁿

Why pick Amersham, a tiny suburb of London most have never heard of and many tourists don't consider? Well... it just so happens my husband lived here for years as a kid, and it was such a special experience to be able to head to spots he remembered, past the old farmhouse he lived in, to the toystore and chip shop he remembered clearly... it was such a cool experience to show our kids where dad spent his years at the ages they are right now!

Even if you don't have a connection to this quiet, cozy Chilterns town, Old Amersham is a great spot to visit just outside of London - my kids LOVE London, but they enjoyed a small country break even more! We went for strolls, drives through a snowy countryside, checked out old churches and popped into the most adorable boutique shops. Can someone arrange a visa for me? I'd move in tomorrow!! 🤣

We stayed at the townhouse at @kingsarmsoldamersham - which was oozing rustic charm with touches dating to the Tudor period. The entire town was so lovely for the holidays - we can't wait to go back!

I know as an influencer it seems like we’re always running around with tons of people having a blast… but it can be really isolating and surface level and catty and intimidating - I’m someone who has had a lot of hard times with friendships, especially as an adult. I was always a tomboy, so maybe I just didn’t develop the girl friend game early in life? It gets kind of tough sometimes feeling like you’re not a part of the clique, nobody really *really* knows you… putting on a smile and a show like it’s all great and happy.

Find friends who make you uncomfortable with being vulnerable and ok being accepted as is. Find your tribe and even if it takes a last minute get together, where you just get silly drunk and run to the beach to watch sunsets, buy matching sweaters, or eat popcorn in a grocery store parking lot because you’re too busy telling stories to ride your bikes back home… enjoy those friendships. 

Maybe because I always feel like I’m on the outside I appreciate them more when I find them. Honestly? The real stuff is so much better. 

That’s it… that’s the post❤️🫶

Jaffa : a love story in 6

@vibeisrael #jaffa #israel #vibetastes #yafo #🇮🇱

Jaffa is full of special treasures to those willing to find them - the port might be buzzy and touristy, but down a side street in a line of unassuming houses, there's a woman like no other, welcoming guests to her home, inviting them to learn her Arabic recipes with a whole lot of fun and love. One second with Doris, @jaffastoriesandcoffee and you can see why - her passion for telling the story of Arab Christian women in Israel - a minority in a minority - her determination to create a business and own a home mortgage free, to help her husband's coffee roasting company... it's all so magical.

We walked into the yard of Doris' home to a large table full of the fresh fruits and vegetables we would be preparing for a lenten feast, and were met with her huge smile and loud music where we had a short dance break, before cooking together. After we made the most amazing meal, we sat in the shade and ate, followed by Arabic coffee and Lebanese Nights pudding for dessert, as Doris shared more about her life in Israel, her love of her culture, and how she's proud to have created an amazing business and life for herself. 

Thanks to Nice to Meet - Hadas' passion for Jaffa and the stories this special place holds is infectious. Booking a day with her is a must to explore the real side of this ancient neighborhood!

Malabi 🌹🍮❤️ - if you're looking for a light, sweet treat in Israel, look no further than this simple milk based pudding with rose, strawberry, or other sweet syrup! It's a quick refreshing bite from markets and small shops all over 🇮🇱. 

Israeli markets often offer traditional dishes from across Yemen, Iraq, Syria, Morocco, Egypt, Turkey - as well as Europe and all over the world - as many Jews who immigrated to Israel brought dishes from their countries with them. You can find so many amazing dishes from cuisines all over the world walking just a few blocks in an Israeli market!

We had amazing malabi with @vibeisrael on the #vibetastes tour, but my favorite was in the HaTikvah neighborhood with a @bhukatours market tour!

I’ve noticed a disturbing trend on social media lately from (mostly other women) attacking having kids/the thought of motherhood.

Look, I get that you’re tired of people asking you when you’re going to have kids (you shouldn’t be asked that at all) and you owe nobody an explanation of why you’re happy. 

DONT attack kids and being a mom to prove your point though! We get it just as much, and more. Kids aren’t welcome in so many places… and moms get guilt over everything from every angle. 

If you don’t want me to criticize your life choices, stop justifying your life choices compared to mine. Stop welcoming everyone BUT children into spaces. You know how kids grow up to be awesome, amazing people? You show them how to function as one!

I can drop everything and travel the world too - with or without my kids. I can have a late lunch and a social life or sleep in - yes, all with kids. I had to re-prioritize some things to make it work (we homeschool, we live in a multi-generational home to help everyone out, I found an alternative career that keeps me with my kids and allows me to travel) - your life is all how you set it up to be. Want to travel a lot? So do I! 

Stop telling mothers with children they can’t do all these things, or that their life isn’t as satisfying because they are prioritizing something else. 

Thanks for coming to my talk 😜
